<div id="review_258439951" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/258439951" />
    <a title="Manish" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4362792-manish"><img alt="Manish" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1329235740p2/4362792.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/258439951?book_show_action=true">Jan 08, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Manish" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Manish" href="/user/show/4362792-manish">Manish</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer258439951" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11161678824111368035">With google.com and timeofindia.com mentioned in the acknowledgments, one doesn&apos;t have to look further to get a sense of the kind of book that Chanakya&apos;s Chant is. Narrating two parallel stories side by side - that of Chanakya and the other of a modern day political strategist and his protege, the book ends up appearing as a school boy attempt at historical fiction. The terrible book also proves that a PhD in Creative Writing is no yardstick to measure the quality of the author. Worth avoiding i</span>
  <span id="freeText11161678824111368035" style="display:none">With google.com and timeofindia.com mentioned in the acknowledgments, one doesn't have to look further to get a sense of the kind of book that Chanakya's Chant is. Narrating two parallel stories side by side - that of Chanakya and the other of a modern day political strategist and his protege, the book ends up appearing as a school boy attempt at historical fiction. The terrible book also proves that a PhD in Creative Writing is no yardstick to measure the quality of the author. Worth avoiding if you're a serious reader! </span>
