<div id="review_357254418" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/357254418" />
    <a title="Ajay" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8543637-ajay"><img alt="Ajay" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1418915105p2/8543637.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/357254418?book_show_action=true">Jun 28, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ajay" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ajay" href="/user/show/8543637-ajay">Ajay</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer357254418" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1577806279772927833">There are certain stories where we would be awestruck with either in the language part and some times the vice versa i.e with the story line. I found this particular pick , excelling in both the terms. The author has did a deep research in bringing out this book. Initially I thought, It was just a historical fiction. But the comparitive writing and linking the old chanakya&apos;s methodology with the modern day Ganagasagar&apos;s , the author has shown his due diligence in bringing out the story line of t</span>
  <span id="freeText1577806279772927833" style="display:none">There are certain stories where we would be awestruck with either in the language part and some times the vice versa i.e with the story line. I found this particular pick , excelling in both the terms. The author has did a deep research in bringing out this book. Initially I thought, It was just a historical fiction. But the comparitive writing and linking the old chanakya's methodology with the modern day Ganagasagar's , the author has shown his due diligence in bringing out the story line of the book. Never a page, I lost my interest in reading, though the book is some what bigger. In my watch and experience of reading certain books of this genre, most of the authors are so inclined towards the story part and some where the readers will be struck with the fictional part and not a lesson will be learnt or realised at the end. But reading wise, you will find as if you were in a heaven in those kind of books. But here, there is a moral in every episode of the story. There is a rationale behind every other scene.<br /><br />Of all the stuffs, the punch lines of both chanakya's and Ganagsagar's are very catchy. The following is my favourite.<br /><br />"You should keep your enemies closer than your friends".</span>
  <a data-text-id="1577806279772927833" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
